    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.16.29"/>
                
                <note type="curatorial">Missouri Collection</note>
                <fw type="curatorial">29</fw>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="caps">UNITED STATES
                        <lb/>
                    DEPARTMENT OF THE INTERIOR
                        <lb/>
                    NATIONAL PARK SERVICE
                        <lb/>
                    YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK
                        <lb/>
                    YELLOWSTONE PARK, WYO.
                        <lb/>
                
                    OFFICE OF THE SUPERINTENDENT</hi>
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>August 20, 1935</dateline>
                
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Mr. John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt,</addrLine>
                            <addrLine>Branson, Missouri.</addrLine>
                    </address>
                    
                    <salute>Dear Mr. Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>Having received so much enjoyment from the "Song of the Indian Wars" and knowing the thorough study that you have made of this period of American history, I am prompted to ask for your assistance.</p>
                
                <p>The Big Hole Battlefield National Monument, in Montana, was established in 1910 and placed under the administration of the War Department. It has recently been transferred, with other historical areas, to the National Park Service. In making plans for the future development of this area the question arises as to whether or not it represents one of the most outstanding events of that portion of American history.</p>
                
                <p>The national parks and monuments represent areas that are of outstanding importance because of their scenic features, scientific features, or prehistoric and historic importance. Among the historical areas the principal periods of American history should be represented. The Colonial, the Revolutionary War, and the Civil War are well represented. The period of the Indian wars should be represented by one or two areas representing the most outstanding events. The Custer Battlefield is now under Federal control as a national cemetery under the administration of the War Department. The Big Hole Battlefield is the only other area representing this period.</p>
                
                <p>I would like very much to have your opinion as to the two or three events of the Indian wars that are most important in our national history. Importance may be measured in several different ways. One engagement might represent the greatest number of men engaged, another might represent the greatest number of casualties, and others might represent critical events the results of which were of importance.</p>
                
                <p>If you can give me the benefit of your advice on this subject it will be deeply appreciated. For many years I have been a great admirer of your work and have been especially impressed by the clear and graphic portrayal of both the Indian point of view and the white man's point of view.</p>  
                <closer>
                    <salute>Sincerely yours,</salute>
                    <signed>Roger W. Toll</signed>
                    <signed>Roger W. Toll
                    Superintendent.</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
